
# VMcore Analysis Script — Red Hat Linux

## Overview

This script automates the initial steps of analyzing a Linux kernel crash dump (vmcore) on Red Hat and Red Hat-compatible systems (Rocky Linux, AlmaLinux, CentOS Stream).

When a Linux kernel panics, it writes a memory dump (vmcore) to disk. Analyzing that dump requires matching kernel debug symbols and the `crash` utility. This script handles the setup and launches the analysis automatically, making it easier to identify the root cause of a kernel panic without having to manually locate packages or remember each command.

Important: This script must be run on a system with the same kernel version as the machine that generated the vmcore. The kernel debug symbols must match exactly.

For background on vmcore analysis methodology, refer to the following documentation:
https://people.redhat.com/pladd/NYRHUG_kdump_and_intro_to_vmcore_analysis.pdf


## Requirements

- Red Hat, Rocky Linux, AlmaLinux, or CentOS Stream
- Root privileges (`sudo`)
- Internet or repository access to download `kernel-debuginfo` packages
- The vmcore file accessible on the local filesystem



## Usage

sudo bash vmcore-analysis.sh

The script will prompt for:

1. Kernel version of the crashed system | `5.14.0-284.11.1.el9_2.x86_64` |
2. Full path to the vmcore file | `/var/crash/2024-01-15-10:30/vmcore` |



## What the Script Does

1. Package check
Verifies that `crash` and `kexec-tools` are installed. Installs any missing packages via `dnf`.

2. Input collection
Prompts for the kernel version and vmcore path, and validates both before proceeding.

3. Debug symbol installation
Downloads and installs `kernel-debuginfo` for the specified kernel version from the appropriate debug repositories. Falls back to `debuginfo-install` if the standard method does not find the package.

4. vmlinux location
Locates the `vmlinux` debug kernel image under `/usr/lib/debug`. If it is not found at the expected path, the script searches for it automatically.

5. Crash analysis
Launches the `crash` utility and automatically runs the following diagnostic commands:

sys: System information 
uname: Kernel version confirmed from the dump
mod: Kernel modules loaded at time of crash
bt: Backtrace — identifies the panic reason and call stack 

All output is saved to `/var/log/vmcore-analysis.log`.



## After the Script Runs

Review the output with focus on:

- bt — the backtrace is usually the fastest path to the root cause, showing what the kernel was doing at the moment of panic
- mod — look for third-party or unexpected kernel modules that may have contributed
- sys/uname — confirm the debug symbols matched the crashed kernel correctly

To continue analysis interactively:


crash /usr/lib/debug/lib/modules/<kernel-version>/vmlinux /var/crash/<timestamp>/vmcore




## Log File

All script output and crash analysis results are written to:


/var/log/vmcore-analysis.log




## Repository Enablement

If the script cannot find `kernel-debuginfo` automatically, you may need to enable the appropriate debug repository manually before re-running:

RHEL:

subscription-manager repos --enable=rhel-*-debug-rpms


Rocky Linux / AlmaLinux:

dnf config-manager --enable baseos-debug


